TY  - JOUR
T1  - Expressive Writing and Coping with Job Loss
AU  - Spera, Stefanie P.
AU  - Buhrfeind, Eric D.
AU  - Pennebaker, James W.
Y1  - 1994/06/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256708
DO  - 10.5465/256708
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 722
EP  - 733
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In an experiment with 63 recently unemployed professionals, those assigned to write about the thoughts and emotions surrounding their job loss were reemployed more quickly than those who wrote about non- traumatic topics or who did not write at all. Expressive writing appeared to influence individuals' attitudes about their old jobs and about finding new employment rather than their motivation to seek employment.
AB  - In an experiment with 63 recently unemployed professionals, those assigned to write about the thoughts and emotions surrounding their job loss were reemployed more quickly than those who wrote about non- traumatic topics or who did not write at all. Expressive writing appeared to influence individuals' attitudes about their old jobs and about finding new employment rather than their motivation to seek employment.
