TY  - JOUR
T1  - Assessing the Relationship between Industry Characteristics and Organizational Culture: How Different can You Be?
AU  - Chatman, Jennifer A.
AU  - Jehn, Karen A.
Y1  - 1994/06/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256699
DO  - 10.5465/256699
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 522
EP  - 553
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigated the relationship between two industry characteristics, technology and growth, and organizational culture. We examined this relationship by comparing the cultures of organizations within and across industries. Using 15 firms representing four industries in the service sector, we found that stable organizational culture dimensions existed and varied more across industries than within them. Specific cultural values were associated with levels of industry technology and growth. One implication of this finding is that the use of organizational culture as a competitive advantage may be more constrained than researchers and practitioners have suggested.
AB  - This study investigated the relationship between two industry characteristics, technology and growth, and organizational culture. We examined this relationship by comparing the cultures of organizations within and across industries. Using 15 firms representing four industries in the service sector, we found that stable organizational culture dimensions existed and varied more across industries than within them. Specific cultural values were associated with levels of industry technology and growth. One implication of this finding is that the use of organizational culture as a competitive advantage may be more constrained than researchers and practitioners have suggested.
