TY  - JOUR
T1  - Role of Protégé Personality in Receipt of Mentoring and Career Success
AU  - Turban, Daniel B.
AU  - Dougherty, Thomas W.
Y1  - 1994/06/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256706
DO  - 10.5465/256706
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 688
EP  - 702
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We used structural equation modeling to investigate relationships among protégés' personality characteristics, initiation of mentoring, mentoring received, and career success for 147 managers and professionals. Protégés influenced the amounts of mentoring they received by initiating relationships with mentors. Internal locus of control, high self-monitoring, and high emotional stability enhanced initiation, which mediated the relationships between personality characteristics and mentoring received. The latter was related to career attainment and perceived career success, and career attainment influenced perceived success. Finally, protégé gender was not related to initiation or mentoring received.
AB  - We used structural equation modeling to investigate relationships among protégés' personality characteristics, initiation of mentoring, mentoring received, and career success for 147 managers and professionals. Protégés influenced the amounts of mentoring they received by initiating relationships with mentors. Internal locus of control, high self-monitoring, and high emotional stability enhanced initiation, which mediated the relationships between personality characteristics and mentoring received. The latter was related to career attainment and perceived career success, and career attainment influenced perceived success. Finally, protégé gender was not related to initiation or mentoring received.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256706
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256706
Y2  - 2026/04/24
